document.docTitle: Thyestetha lubrica Eberle & Riedel, sp. n.
document.masterDocTitle: Revision and phylogenetic analysis of the Papuan weevil genus Thyestetha Pascoe (Coleoptera, Curculionidae, Cryptorhynchinae)

mods:titleInfo.mods:title: Revision and phylogenetic analysis of the Papuan weevil genus Thyestetha Pascoe (Coleoptera, Curculionidae, Cryptorhynchinae)

subSubSection.paragraph: Rostrum 5.2 X as long as wide at base. Head. Vertex medially and next to eye with distinct punctures.

Prothorax 1.2 X wider than long; anterior 1 / 4 of disc punctate with small punctures, remainder subglabrous and with minute punctures (except for row of coarse punctures along base); sides punctate with small punctures; postocular lobe coarsely punctate with larger punctures; marginal carina externally along edge with few whitish scales; inner surface of rostral canal with scattered long setae.

Elytra as long as wide; sides rounded; apex slightly extended, jointly rounded; striae effaced on elytral disc, striae 8 and 9 apically distinct; interstices between punctures of stria 8 equal to diameter of punctures, interstices between punctures of stria 9 small. Metanepisternum 3.4 X wider than high.

Thoracic venter. Meso- and metaventrite laterally with sparse small scales; metaventrite submedially behind mesocoxa with pair of moderate protrusions. Pro- and mesocoxa densely punctate, squamose; metacoxa glabrous; trochanter with sparse, coarse punctures containing small scales. Distance between mesocoxae subequal to width of mesocoxa.

Legs. Femora basally sparsely punctate, apically denser, scales slender; meso- and metafemur dorsally with broader scales; metafemur with denser scaling, dorsal squamose line moderately dense; anteroventral ridges relatively weak with posteroventral ridge in apical third moderately protruding.
Abdomen. Ventrite 1 laterally and center of ventrite 2 with few thin scales arising from punctures; remaining ventrites subglabrous except lateral margins slightly squamose.

Terminalia. Aedeagus (
Figs. 45–46
). Apex strongly curved ventrad, sides sinuate, converging; lateral orificial sclerites small, outer portion
2– 3
X longer than inner portion; anterior median orificial sclerite with small bulge between 2 nd and 3 rd fold (as in
Fig. 35
). Transfer apparatus in profile weakly incised at middle, ventral contour angularly projecting; anterior and posterior ends curved ventrad; in dorsal view strongly constricted at middle, anterior portion narrower than posterior portion. Sclerotized part of ventral membrane extending proximad 0.75 X length of aedeagal body from insertion of apodemes.

Allotype, female. Same as holotype except: Rostrum 5.43 X longer than wide. Prothorax 1.21 X longer than wide. Elytra 1.04 X longer than wide; extreme apex slightly more slender. Metafemur without concavity basal to stridulatory patch, posteroventral ridge not protruding. Terminalia. Hemisternites of ovipositor 5.75 X longer than wide. Tergite VII 1.44 X longer than wide. Tergite VIII 2.73 X longer than wide. Bursal sclerite at insertion of spermathecal duct weakly sclerotized.

Intraspecific variation. Length, males 2.8–4.5 mm (n= 9 , x = 4.1 mm ± 0.6 mm ), females 3.0– 4.5 mm (n= 13 , x = 4.1 mm ± 0.5 mm ). Color of body black or dark ferruginous (in a few specimens); two teneral specimens from Wannang-village with ferruginous elytra contrasting to black pronotum. Aedeagus with apex less markedly curved in some specimen from Madang. Spermathecal cornu moderately to strongly curved.
Etymology. The epithet is based on the Latin adejective lubricus, -a, -um (slippery) and refers to the smooth and slippery body of this species.
